<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="53" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[140,1108,307,510]" pageId="2" pageNumber="53">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[140,271,307,333]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="53" reason="1">Comments</emphasis>
. Previous authors have recognized two subgenera – 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moure" authorityYear="1941" box="[871,997,307,333]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Habralictus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" sensu="stricto">
<emphasis box="[871,997,307,333]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="53">Habralictus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1006,1057,308,334]" pageId="2" pageNumber="53" sensu="stricto">s.str.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moure" authorityYear="1941" box="[140,252,343,369]" class="Insecta" family="Hymenoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Zikaniella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[140,252,343,369]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="53">Zikaniella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
– based on characters such as the width of head and genae, the concavity of the clypeus, and the shape of the metatibial spur serrate or pectinate (
<bibRefCitation author="Michener CD" box="[914,1095,378,404]" pageId="2" pageNumber="53" refId="ref2794" refString="Michener CD (2007) Th e Bees of the World [2 nd Edition]. Johns Hopkins University Press, Baltimore, xvi + [i] + 953 pp." type="book" year="2007">Michener 2007</bibRefCitation>
). The species described herein combines some of these characters (clypeus not concave and flat, genae narrower than compound eyes, and pectinate metatibial spurs), supporting the unification of the subgenera as used by Moure et al. (2007).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
